The Ukrainian parliament today rejected a proposal to repeal a paragraph under the amendment to the Criminal Code on the basis of which opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko was convicted.
An amendment that would pave the way for the release of the jailed ex-premier, MEPs rejected at the second reading of the proposal to reduce penalties for economic offences.
Tymoshenko was sentenced in October to seven years in prison for allegedly concluding an unfavourable contract with Russia to buy natural gas.
The judgment is not valid, the appeal of the sentenced person is to be heard by the court in December.
Tymoshenko describes the verdict as a political vengeance of the regime, a suspicion from the preoccupation of the court has provoked a trial in the West.
The proposal to remove section 365 of the Criminal Code, on the basis of which the former prime minister was sentenced, was supported by 147 MPs in the vote.
It needed 226 votes to approve it.
