Need for Speed: The Run races across America.
<0xE2><0x86><0x90> Reviews
Originally a carefree ride, due to a series of completely unnecessary slutty mistakes, turns into a routine morning ride on the Shish.
Although the ambition was largely fulfilled, it is not valid if no one clearly wanted to do anything extra.
A new part with the subtitle The Run aroused high expectations before the release.
He promised that over the years, the Need for Speed racing series would again move a bit in a new direction and from playable shows it appeared as a game that would not have to be just a number in the action racing genre.
We were also curious as to how the inserted passages would turn out, in which the main hero would get out of the car and run on his own.
But as is the custom with the NFS series, many are a little different than we expected.
These are potentially decent arcade races, but the whole pulls down a few unnecessary bugs that have been appearing in the series for more or less several years.
So these are not actually mistakes, but rather manifestations of some incomprehensible laziness of the developers.
The adventure begins very well.
You are introduced to a story whose main character Jack has certain personal problems and as a solution offers to participate in an illegal race across America.
You will sit behind the wheel on the west coast of San Francisco and your task is to be the first to arrive in New York.
The idea carries with it several interesting elements.
The track is divided into ten stages, and then into more than fifty races.
It follows that each race goes on a different track and the stages are set in different, sufficiently different and interesting environments.
You don’t feel like the game is always the same.
In addition, some of the environments are very nice to look at, although the technical level of the graphics corresponds to the previous parts of the series.
So it's nothing world-class.
But driving across the desert, through the autumn landscape or high in the snowy mountains looks visually very pleasant.
In addition, races are occasionally laced with some atypical element.
In the desert, for example, you wind up in a sandstorm, which greatly reduces visibility.
On the other hand, in the mountains, you have to be careful not to be overrun by an avalanche.
In addition, the individual races are set up quite well behind each other.
There are only a few types, but that’s enough.
For a while you try to pass the desired number of opponents (essentially a classic race), then you catch up with time (a classic duel with stops) and then you wait for a duel with a single opponent.
From time to time, the police will also be involved in this, which makes all your efforts even more unpleasant.
New are the passages outside the car.
It’s more of an interactive animation where Jack usually runs away from someone and you have to help him by pressing the right buttons at the right times.
It's not complicated.
Surprised, though, that these passages are much less in the game than you would expect (specifically, maybe even only three).
As a result, however, this is beneficial, because this element does not have a chance to become annoying and in the context of what has been said, it belongs to the elements that diversify the game.
The driving model follows in the footsteps of previous parts.
This means that it is definitely not a thing nowadays, but it can not be said that it would be a negative.
If you are looking for a realistic simulation, you will need to look elsewhere.
But the more action-packed racing here, the driving model still fits quite well, even though we could find a better one in the competition.
Until then, everything is in perfect order.
Problems begin to appear after a while.
Unlike the driving model, the collision model is no longer in order.
From the game of this type, we do not expect to calculate complex deformations and collisions, but if you have no idea how your car will behave before practically any impact on any object, then probably not everything is perfectly fine.
Typically, when passing or passing cars in normal traffic, sometimes you only lick each other lightly, but at other times in an almost identical situation, your car will end up in wild pirouettes.
Or even a direct attack.
Thanks to the system of restarts, it does not matter at all, but it will disassemble you reliably.
Restarts are solved so that if you break up or go far off track, the game throws you back to the last catching point on the track.
However, there are only five reboots available in each race.
When you exhaust them, you have to start the race again from the beginning.
So it’s more of an aid in case something fails than you can rely on it.
But sometimes even restarts will not help, they will only solve the need to learn the given section of the race from memory.
The big problem with the game is that the same things often happen in the same places.
Some corners, for example, need to be crossed in a specific way, otherwise you simply do not fit into them.
Other times you will meet "civil" cars in the same configuration at a given location, whether you arrive there first, fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is especially annoying when you see the opponent pass easily in front of you between two opposing cars, while when you get there, the cars are already in such a position that you have to bypass or brake them.
It doesn’t matter when you get to them, because it’s “calculated” so that the situation always happens right in front of your nose.
Competitors have another advantage.
Throughout the game, you will encounter several places where, again, regardless of the time, you will always be ahead of the same opponent in the same place.
Most of all, it breaks at the end of the game on a long bridge, where you go in the opposite direction.
The opponent must get there before you, obviously, at any cost.
When he drives in front of you, it makes the view of the cars against you worse, so at first you get a couple of nice smears.
You can understand the intent to make the game more exciting and adrenaline-pumping, but the execution is so obvious that it will reliably dislike you quickly.
And it's a shame, because despite the simple driving model, it's fun to play and places even so action-packed that sometimes you literally don't want to watch what's flying.
And basically it doesn’t matter if it has a concept with fifty unique tracks, sorting the races so that boredom doesn’t have a chance, or anything else.
An unusual idea is to change cars during races.
You have to be careful about the petrol pumps on the road, because it is there that you can change the car, although in the vast majority of cases you will suffice with what you just have.
Cars are divided into three categories.
Sports cars are suitable for urban areas, strong American turbulence on straight highways and exotic supersports for technical riding, for example on rugged mountain trails.
With the main story mode goes hand in hand and challenge mode, which are races in individual locations that you know from the story.
Here you get not only medals, but also experience points in your profile, which is common for challenges and story.
To get a higher level of the driver, various objects are unlocked: starting with cars and ending with the background for the profile.
At the same time, it is again connected to the online Autolog feature, which among other things compares your achieved results with other players and provides other community features.
One of the other hard-to-understand kicks is the situation from the last race in the story.
With your car you get to the subway tunnel (besides), where you ride it in the dark on the tracks (besides).
On the speedometer you flash numbers between 150 and 200 km/h (yet) and in that a set of metro arrives from the rear and uncompromisingly crashes you.
In the editorial office, we will probably have a discussion for a few more days about whether no one really thought a little when creating the game, or whether the authors think we are really such big fools.
The technical side of the game is nothing extra, but at least the overall visual impression is in most cases very pleasant and in a few cases even great.
It freezes so that in some more intense moments the imaging decreases, and in some cases quite tragically.
But this is especially true for turrets with a larger number of participants, when smooth imaging would no longer be valid for you.
The sound page is fine and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to please the widest range of younger audiences, a soundtrack from the category "every dog in a different village" was created, but it can be assumed that due to listening to music, no one will buy the game.
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run is so frustrating.
If the game were to avoid completely unnecessary mistakes, then we would not be afraid to say that The Run is the best work by NFS in the last few years.
This is how the game works unfinished.
Fun is definitely fine, but be prepared that the mistakes will rip you in the eyes with the force of the airport headlights.
