IBM Innovator Begins Second Century of Its Existence
If someone were looking for a word that would most accurately express IBM’s strategy, perhaps the closest would be “longevity.”
For the general public, IBM is a symbol of the technological revolution, it is a company perceived as very contemporary, and yet it has been a hundred years since it was founded.
The basis of this long-term was laid by the first head of the company, visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He has already coined the slogan that a number of world problems can be easily solved if people are willing to think.
His slogan "Think!" became the imprint around which the life of the future giant will unfold (and also the name of an internal magazine that began to be published at IBM as early as 1935).
It was also the basis of Watson’s carefully built corporate culture.
“For us at IBM, long-term thinking means a continuous movement towards the future.
IBM survived and prospered for a hundred years because it remained true to its core values and was not afraid to change everything else around it.
This allowed us to transform technology, business and society during our first century.
We hope to achieve even more in the second hundred," said Samuel J. Palmisano, the company's current CEO.
A well-developed system
In the 1930s, Watson approached the care of his employees in the same way as the entrepreneur of Bata in the Czech Republic - people from IBM had paid holidays as one of the first American employees, insurance from the employer plus an elegant employee uniform and an elaborate business system for rewarding the best employees.
IBM also has a long-term relationship with the customer.
From the start, the company was brilliant at extracting talent - as one of the world's first companies, it abolished any discrimination, so it could choose.
In line with the anti-discrimination strategy, the current plan is for Palmisana to be replaced next year by a woman - Virginia Rometty.
She has worked at IBM for 30 years and is still the head of sales, marketing and strategy.
In recent years, IBM has been making so-called pitfalls, online brainstorming, from which many future strategies and innovations emerge.
No wonder there are enough ideas - almost half a million people work in the company.
Institutions with a good name
A firm position in the business is ensured by its strong internal and external image.
“In the beginning, IBM had the concept of an institution rather than just a technology company,” said Harvard Business School professor and author of the book on IBM, Rosabeth Moss Kanter.
“IBM is not a technology company, but a company that helps solve business problems through the use of technology,” said George Colony of Forrester Research.
As the company itself says, the difference between entering the market and creating the market directly.
IBM – or “Big Blue” as it is known for its logo in the United States – has grown into one of the world’s largest companies in a hundred years.
It is probably the most versatile technology company - it develops hardware and software, infrastructure, hosting and consulting services in a range of products from servers to nanotechnology.
It holds the most patents of all U.S. technology companies, and five of its employees have won the Nobel Prize.
Its inventions include, for example, an ATM, a credit card, a financial swap, a barcode or a floppy disk.
IBM, with approximately $220 billion, became the second-largest technology company by market capitalization this year (the first is Apple), when it surpassed Microsoft for the first time since 1996.
A Look Ahead
Not all products and innovations matched the tastes of customers and the times - for example, IBM failed to bet on its own OS/2 operating system, Prodigy online services or IBM PCjr computers.
“If your business is built to move forward, you can’t emotionally tie yourself to the past,” Samuel J. Palmisano said.
That’s why IBM has no problem building its foundations on many platforms – and if they don’t work, then leave them.
Unlike, for example, the competing Microsoft, which basically stands and falls on the Windows operating system.
Perspective technologies
IBM has the largest share of services in its revenues, after about five percent it is made up of software and hardware.
In 1990, with more than half the share, it was the strongest representative of hardware.
Since 2000, IBM has sold low-yield assets worth $15 billion, while in the same period it has invested $58 billion in the purchase of promising technologies.
Investment has continued since 2008, when the modern financial crisis overtook the world for the first time.
IBM is acting on the legacy of its first chief executive, Thomas J. Watson, who also increased investment during the Great Depression.
So far, it seems that IBM is going through the current crisis unaffected.
The price of IBM shares has risen by 120 percent since the beginning of 2008, and the company's net profit is continuously growing.
IBM’s motto is to change everything, but not your values.
Therefore, it can be expected that even if another crisis comes, this flexible giant will manage it.
IBM History: From Cheese Cutter to Space Flight
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York City a hundred years ago, originally under the complex name Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
IBM took over the name in 1924 - originally a brand used for the company's branches in Canada and South America.
IBM was founded by a merger of four companies, whose history dates back to the 1980s.
They possessed technologies such as the famous "walkers", i.e. the clocks recording the arrival and departure of the employee.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who also chaired the company's supervisory board until 1930.
Flint hired Thomas J. Watson, the head of a rival company, to help him manage the company.
The leader then overshadowed the founders of IBM - Watson's ideas are still built on an invincible corporate culture and identity.
Watson led the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name suggests, began with the production and sale of all kinds of machines for business - from meat and cheese cutters to cash registers.
During the first four years of Watson’s leadership, the company’s turnover doubled to $9 million, and the company’s extensive expansion to all continents began.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that after almost forty years in the boss's chair, he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence, developing the first programming language.
In the 1960s, people and computers from IBM helped NASA drive flights to space — to Mercury, Saturn, and in 1969, the famous human flight to the moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers - the IBM System/360 series.
The classic "pécécéco" that set the computer standard of the time, called IBM 5150, came on the market in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold the production of computers to Chinese company Lenovo, on the contrary, bought the consulting part of PricewaterhouseCoopers and began to devote itself fully to consulting and services with high added value.
The strategy that has paid off in IBM’s last three years is the concept of the Smarter Planet, the “smarter planet”.
Its aim is to make smart use of technologies in previously unplanned areas and to improve the situation, for example in transport or urban management.
IBM recently introduced the “Smarter Commerce” platform to help retailers manage the entire business cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in the country.
It founded its branch in Czechoslovakia in 1932 as the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, in addition to IBM, the Czech Republic also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The Central Office for Central and Eastern Europe is based in Prague and there is also a world-class research team dealing with voice recognition.
