How Travel Prices Have Evolved Since 1989
Until 1989, only five state travel agencies were allowed in Czechoslovakia: <0xC4><0x8C>edok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Travel agencies at that time sold in the overwhelming majority only trips to the countries of the socialist bloc, as travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists thus travelled on holiday to the sea to the GDR (German Democratic Republic), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Crimea near the Black Sea), to Bulgaria, Romania (both to the Black Sea) and to Hungary (Balaton).
The bright exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when it was also possible to travel to Yugoslavia, but then the Yugoslav regime bowed to the West and the journeys of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia were subsequently very limited.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel individually freely even within socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or to the Soviet Union, he needed a letter of invitation from this country, otherwise an individual journey was not possible.
Travel agencies at the time also offered trips to the West, but it was necessary to stand the line overnight with a sleeping bag or have a "well-known" travel agency.
However, it was not won either.
The so-called currency promise, which was a condition for travel to the West, was not given to “politically unreliable people” who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so it was not possible to obtain funds (the Western currency) for a trip to the West without a currency promise.
However, by far the most common Czechs spent their holidays in the country, which resulted in a large number of cottages and chalets that the Czechs had taken and this custom survives to this day.
The travel of the Czechs has experienced a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria were our maxim, last year Czechs spent 4.5 million holidays abroad in countries around the world.
The enormous paradox that we are no longer aware of today is that it was not possible for us to travel freely to the currently most popular Croatia until 1989, since it was part of then Yugoslavia.
At the end of the 1990s, the visa requirement for neighbouring Western European countries was lifted, triggering a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Austria’s Vienna and Germany.
Czechoslovaks could not get tired of trips to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to look there for a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czechs were sleeping in parks in tents, because our income at the time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or guesthouse.
A typical feature of the travel of the Czechs at this time was to drive their own food, canned food, salami, etc. to save money.
Another important moment was the introduction of a freely exchangeable Czech crown, so that our tourists could finally freely buy the western currency after many rainy years.
However, our standard of living and thus our average wages have risen, resulting in another important moment around 1997.
As a result of the increased demand for travel, travel agencies have started to prepare travel regularly since 1997 by charter airlines, which has resulted in an incredible reduction in air travel thanks to the possibility to negotiate quantitative discounts compared to the past.
By the end of the 1990s, Czechs had already had visa-free access to virtually all the developed countries of the world, except the United States, which further facilitated our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary travel occurred in 2000, when, thanks to considerable demand, the Czech Republic was historically the first direct charter flight to exoticism, it was to Thailand.
From this year every year direct charter flights with Czech tourists to warm faraway countries, this winter will fly directly from the Czech Republic to twelve exotic destinations.
Exotic countries are currently visited by around 100,000 Czechs a year!
Another interesting moment in this period, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the U.S. abolished the visa for Czech tourists, making our country one of the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, Czechs also spent more than half of their holidays abroad for the first time in history (50.3%) and for the first time in history spent more than CZK 15,000 per person on one foreign holiday, including costs at the place of residence.
