Peter Englund’s emotionally powerful new book Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War begins with a long list of prominent characters that turns your head.
One piece of advice on how to keep up at the moment: Carefully pull out this page and make a bookmark out of it.
You will get to know all the people in Mr. Englund's novel story very well, and this list will serve as a navigational guide - like a beacon - at a time when, like the men and women in the story, you will feel confused and lost in different situations.
Mr. Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also a new deputy to the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize for Literature.
The book we are talking about here is very unusual - the author himself describes it quite aptly, as "an antihistorical work".
It contains several very well-known names, important treaties or famous battles, on the contrary, it almost lacks ambassadors, energetic journalists and debates about tactics and equipment.
It is not so much a book about what happened, explains the author, as rather "a book about what it was like". It deals mainly with "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods".
"Beauty and Grief" combines the war experiences of 20 less than a dozen men and women, on both sides of the barricade, from students and botanists to climbers, doctors, rescue drivers and officials.
Some of these people will become heroes.
Others will become prisoners of war, lose limbs, go crazy, or die.
Their lives flicker like the flames of candles lit in the church - new ones are added to the web of fate, while others are extinguished.
Mr. Englund’s book is different from classic historical novels.
It corrects the notion that World War I was all about the terrifying trench battles on the Western Front.
"Beauty and Grief" skilfully explores other places where war dramas took place: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
Soldiers in this book solve problems with falling bee nests on them, having to spend Christmas in the shadow of pyramids or struggling with the presence of tse-tse flies.
From the very beginning, it was a very touching read.
War will devour people's lives like a natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina smelling of gunpowder.
When gunfire starts to ring in the distance and you are the woman who is at home with your children, will you run away or stay?
Who's actually getting close?
Almost no one understands what is going on, not even why the whole war was started.
“The vacuum created by the lack of facts,” observed Mr. Englund, “was filled with speculations, conjectures, hopes, fears, prejudices, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumors.”
"Beauty and Grief" follows the stories of individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young sailor serving in the German fleet.
Their stories are all taken from biographies, letters and other materials already published.
Descriptions of their lives may sound frightening and compelling, but with the inclusion of tiny moments and details, they are absolutely vivid and believable.
Many of them talk about suffering and coping with it.
In the story of a German student, the author says: "Replacements, everywhere the same substitutes."
"Coffee substitute, aluminum imitation, rubber imitation, paper bandages, wooden buttons."
He goes even further and describes food substitutes in Germany.
It mentions "meat made from pressed rice cooked in scop fat (and supplemented by a fake bone made of wood), tobacco from dried roots and dried potato peels, shoes with wooden soles".
It mentions that there were "837 registered meat substitutes in the production of sausages and 511 registered coffee substitutes".
Some stories are about honor and bravery.
One American finds within himself the inner urges to savagery and brutality, and declares of war: "At last you will understand that this is precisely human nature. Not to sit in comfortable chairs with cigars and whiskey, not to pose with this evening newspaper or a good book of yours, and not to pretend to be a barbarian.
On the contrary, the British soldier realizes that he is most likely to die soon and no one will even notice, let alone grieve.
“When one finally reconciles himself with sacrifice, one would expect it to be so in the eyes of a grateful audience,” he writes.
Instead, he feels like a “convict who is being secretly hanged.”
Other remarks relate to the departure of the old Europe and the emergence of new horrors.
"Conflict has increasingly become an economic competition and a competitive struggle," writes Mr. Englund, "a war between factories."
He captured what he says is "a new kind of beast of the coming century: an eloquent and ideologically committed mass murderer in tailor-made dress who performs his bloodshed without getting up from the table."
People behave completely unexpectedly, ugliness alternates with heroism.
Mr. Englund also describes soldiers who deliberately tried to catch a sexual disease from prostitutes in order to avoid service on the front lines.
"The worst example of this behavior was the trade in gonokok pus that soldiers bought and used to fight their genitals in the hopes of ending up in a hospital," he writes.
"The most desperate rubbed it in their eyes, often blinding them for the rest of their lives."
In this translation from the Swedish by Peter Graves, Mr Englund's prose is succinct, but in no way obvious, which fits perfectly with his human subject.
In dozens of small outputs, it captures the way the war “dissolved absolutely uncontrollable forces: extreme nationalism, social revolution, religious hatred.”
People are beginning to wonder why their leaders are forcing them to fight.
