The union of auxiliary workers will sue the city for dismissal
On Wednesday, unions representing hundreds of school aid workers who lost their jobs last month are planning to sue the city, saying layoffs were not necessary and were discrimination because of the disproportionate impact on schools attended by poor students.
The judicial review is probably the last option left for the District Council 37 trade unions in their effort to reverse the dismissal decision.
On October 7, six hundred and seventy-two school assistants, parental coordinators and other employees, who were among the city's worst-paid employees, lost their jobs. Their dismissals were described by union leaders as a retribution for the city's inability to access health care last spring.
The city’s officials categorically denied the accusation.
At a city council meeting last month, education minister Dennis M. Walcott said the dismissal was part of a budget approved in June.
One of the members of the council immediately countered by saying that there was no specific mention of the dismissal of auxiliary staff in the budget.
District Council 37 officials have already filled out the necessary documents and warned the education ministry that they will sue him. They will convene a press conference on Wednesday where they will formally announce a lawsuit before the Supreme State Court in Manhattan.
The defendants in the trial will be Mr. Walcott and the Ministry of Education, while the plaintiff will be eight laid off workers, all of whom are African-American or Hispanic, as well as most of the other assistants who lost their jobs.
Elizabeth Thomas, a spokeswoman for the city’s legal department, said the city had not yet seen the lawsuit and would not comment on the individual charges.
According to a complaint filed by the New York Times, the unions focused on the number of people released in poor parts of the city to back up their claims of unfair treatment, saying that poor schools had lost more financial assistants because they had been drinking for a long time.
They point out that while schools in Staten Island and the Upper East Side have not been discharged at all, Brooklyn, District 23 in Brownsville, and Districts 8 and 9 in the South Bronx have lost 17 school assistants, and 46 assistants have been discharged.
He recalls that at Public School 36 in Harlem, five out of eight assistants lost their jobs, despite the fact that it is a school where 68 percent of students live in poverty. The lawsuit says: "It is not a neighborhood full of mobile parents who can get funding to make up for the budget deficit."
Public School 36’s budget was cut by 3.26% this year, and the school also lost money when the city changed the way of calculating bonus finances for every enrolled poor student.
The trade unions, among other things, claim that the directors of secondary schools may have been confused by the way in which the document approving the dismissal of the parent coordinators was written.
In the document, the word "excess" was used to describe the event, i.e. to cancel the position, although this word is much more often used to describe the transfer of a teacher from the school's payroll to a database of available workers whose salary is paid by the central authority.
“Sixty-six parental coordinators have been dismissed,” the complaint states, “and not just moved to the database for available staff.”
