The proposal was rejected in the House because of the differing views of both political parties, so it was never even voted on in the Senate.
However, on the same day that this motion was rejected in the House, the Chamber also rejected measures that would stop the financing of US operations in Libya.
As a result, the U.S. mission in Libya literally found itself in a legislative purge – Congress criticized the way President Obama manages the mission, but his members were obviously not so irritated that they stopped supporting him in his actions.
