For the time being, the other legislators, despite considerable efforts, have not yet managed to push their proposals through to the vote itself.
Goodlatt’s proposal is just one of 68 amendments to the constitution that were introduced in Congress and touched on a wide range of different topics.
Some of them were the same - the same proposal submitted to the House and the Senate - and others are only minor changes to others.
Only in the House can be found at least 15 versions of the Balanced Budget Supplement and another handful that would like to "regulate federal spending".
Some of the proposals are identical, but their proponents – especially novice Republicans who want to improve their reputation – can boast of their “authority.”
The revenue on budget regulation, which was approved in August, required both the House and the Senate to vote on the Balanced Budget Addendum.
In March, 58 senators voted in favour of a non-binding declaration to support the creation of such an addendum.
In addition to the budget, several members also want to discuss limits on the number of terms that members of Congress could serve, while José E. Serrano (N.Y.) wants to increase the number of terms that may be in office.
Representative Jesse L. Jackson Jr. (Ill.) offered a range of supplements that would, among other things, guarantee the right to quality education and medical care.
The permanent proposal remains a supplement banning same-sex marriage and a supplement banning the burning of the state flag.
Some lawmakers also want to allow federal laws to be repealed if two-thirds of states oppose them.
Although members of Congress seem to be very active in proposing various additions, they do not significantly outperform the average in comparison with previous years.
In the 111th Congress they offered 77 additions, while in the 100th Congress there were 66.
Their activity even pales in comparison to the early 1990s, when, according to Senate Library statistics, members offered more than 150 additions every two years.
However, they were not much more successful than current politicians.
The last amendment that was added – the 27th Amendment – was ratified in 1992, but was actually proposed by Congress in 1789.
