Walls Have Eyes: How Scientists Explore You on Facebook
Before Anders Behring Breivik became the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, he was just another young man to present his anti-immigrant views online.
On Monday, Braivik, who confessed to the July murderous insanity that left 77 people dead in Norway, attended his first public court hearing.
Although Breivik could act alone, he was definitely not alone in cyberspace: he spent a lot of time at the computer while preparing the attack, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists supporting right-wing groups on social networking sites.
After the tragedy of this summer, scientists want to learn more about these people.
But how to find them?
Easy - just go to Facebook.
“We realized that getting them isn’t really that hard,” says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recent report by a British research team on European digital populism.
The stock of personal information on Facebook is so extensive, Bartlett says, that it was enough for scientists to simply use the ads on the site and, thanks to it, determine with absolute accuracy the demographic group they were looking for - something that marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett's team across Europe found half a million fans of right-wing groups to be attracted to them, and they turned their attention to them and sent them advertisements. However, instead of inviting them through them to the newly formed group or offering them some diet products, they asked them to meet their needs.
Through Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues managed to get results from more than 10,000 fans of 14 different right-wing groups in 11 European countries – without ever having to leave the office.
“It’s a completely new way of doing research,” Bartlett notes.
Some of the results are not so surprising: online supporters of right-wing groups are all young men who are denounced by the increasing rate of immigration.
But on the other hand, “those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic, and less violent than those who remain constantly hidden behind a computer screen.”
The work of the DEMOS team is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new tool in the hands of scientists.
Research teams, health scientists and political researchers use this site to study everything from health issues to social trends hidden by state updates, posts on the walls and pressing "Like" buttons.
Facebook reports more than 800 million active users. On average, each of them will provide three different data per day, making this social network literally a "information supernova", which is behind the development of many new research. The number of academic papers, in which the word Facebook appears in front of their name, has increased by 800%.
For some scientists, the magic of Facebook is that it gives them the opportunity to study people without having to bother them somewhere on the street.
"It used to be that when you wanted to do a poll among people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
“You’d have to get to a place where you’d never be let go,” Bartlett says.
“Facebook is breaking this down – you’re just going straight to them.”
Others claim that the site can offer a way to identify a social-health problem and avoid them.
In a recent study by Dr. Megan Morena of the University of Wisconsin, a research team found that university students who analyzed their drinking outcomes on Facebook were much more at risk of alcoholism than students who were silent on the topic.
Morena suggests that students’ peers monitor the site and come up with an offer to help a student who posts too many drunken statuses.
"The problem can't be solved unless you can diagnose it," said Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Dr. Morena and director of the Center for Children's Health, Behavior and Development at the Seattle Children's Research Institute.
“We’ve found a way to identify endangered children that we wouldn’t otherwise have a chance to discover.”
Facebook is constantly polling the data of its users.
The information team of the site has compiled statistics on the relationship between the status of the relationship and Valentine's Day, electoral participation in 2010 and the satisfaction rate of the nation (mainly using the information that they had access to - Internet freedom advocates have long claimed that the site should make its informational treasure available for research).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them whether they like it or not – in exchange for the opportunity to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, the site needs to provide their personal information.
But what if Facebook users become part of research they don’t even know about?
Scientists have clearly defined rules on how to collect data offline, but online data is accessible to everyone.
“I don’t think most of the users thought scientists could look at their profiles,” says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, of a 2006 study he conducted using his students’ public Facebook walls.
"As far as they were concerned, they took it to be information only between them and their friends."
There is also the question of methodology.
Even when researching offline, there is no guarantee that the subject is completely honest.
It is not possible to verify on Facebook how much of the information on the profile and posts on the wall are true.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things,” Selwyn explains.
That’s why Selwin, who has spent many years researching new technologies, believes that a pencil and a notebook remain the best possible tool to be used in research.
“When you go out into the real world and talk to real people, it’s something that can’t be replaced,” he says.
“Social research should be about society and social activities – and a hell of a lot of social activities are still happening offline.”
