It is this material, slightly trimmed, that forms the basis of the 68-minute film Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which is heading to selected cinemas this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone who has become famous for his reluctance to provide longer interviews, here Jobs seems surprisingly excited to be able to talk about his technological philosophy and business strategies.
He also appears to be a very thoughtful person.
Four times during the interview, there will be a longer pause between the question and the answer - 10 to 15 seconds of thinking, when it is possible to see how Jobs perfectly thinks the answer to be as accurate and as accurate as possible.
There are also moments when Jobs’ perfectionism comes to the surface, when he acts impatiently at Cringely’s questions and encourages him to get to more important problems and topics faster.
The interview was filmed before the era of Pixar, iPod, or iPhone, and there are scary prophetic thoughts in it as Jobs evaluates what other companies are doing right and wrong while offering his own vision of the future in the field of computer technology.
It’s one thing to read Job’s posthumous assessments of his career, but on Jobs, whom we see here as a keen dreamer in the bloom of his genius, there’s something raw and inspiring.
Here he has his own vision of what things could and should look like.
It didn’t take long, and after he had spoken his thoughts, he began to put them into practice as well.
A quick summary of seven scenes from the Lost Interview, which is definitely worth noting:
How he learned to run a business:
“Over the years of business, I’ve always asked, ‘Why are you doing this?’ and the answer was always the same: ‘Well, that’s just how it’s done.’
No one knows why he does what he does, he never thinks deeply about things related to business.
That's what I found out.
Jobs continues by describing his efforts to simplify accounting at Apple.
He was completely confused by the way the costs were recorded - they often started with the inscription "standard costs", about their amount he could only imagine. At that moment he decided to go his own way - he developed an automatic tool that guaranteed that they could determine the business costs in a moment.
How he performed the Rosary on the Pope:
Jobs recalls the "Blue Box" he built with Steve Wozniak - a device that allowed people to effectively hack into a phone company and call for free anywhere in the world.
