It tells how Wozniak and his devices were tested using a paid phone and switched from one AT&T network to another while using as many satellites as possible.
“At least half a dozen times we went around the world like this, so when we yelled something into a pay phone, it sounded a minute later from the other phone at the door,” Jobs laughs.
“We were young, and we found that we can build something that is capable of managing infrastructure for billions of dollars around the world.”
The two of us made a little thing that could control a much bigger giant - it was an incredible experience and I don't think Apple would ever have been created without it.
In the middle of the night, through the Blue Box, they called the Vatican and asked if they could talk to the pope, pretending to be Henry Kissinger as best they could.
Gradually, higher and higher rank members of the Catholic Church were summoned to speak to the American diplomat in the middle of the night, and only just before they woke up the pope to the phone, the pair of them unraveled and laid down their headset.
How he fell in love with technology (and phoned Bill Hewlett):
When he was 12, he was looking for spare parts to build a barometer, and he found a number on Bill Hewlett's phone book and called him.
Shortly after their 20-minute interview, Jobs had secured a summer brigade at Hewlett-Packard.
"It was the only company I knew at the time, and it shaped my view of what such a company is and how it should treat its employees."
Jobs later became one of HP’s employees who visited the company’s research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw “the first desktop computer ever made.”
