The quintet included the country in its tour on the occasion of the celebration of 20 years of existence
"The journey to Costa Rica is a dream that becomes a reality"
In an exclusive interview for Viva, bassist Jeff Ament of Pearl Jam said the band is ready to offer one of the best concerts at the National Stadium next Sunday.
We have been waiting for more than 20 years, but the group itself assures them that the opportunity to play in Costa Rica is a dream come true.
This is what bassist and founding member Jeff Ament said, who spoke exclusively with Viva last week from Brazil.
The group is on the South American continent as part of a tour to celebrate 20 years of existence and will be at a unique stop in Central America on Sunday 20th.
This day will take place at 19:30 at the National Stadium together with the angel group The X and the national musicians from Las Robertas.
This is a sample of an interview, the full transcript of which can be found on the La Naci<0xC3><0xB3>n website.
For your Costa Rican fans, this is a dream come true. Pearl Jam will play in Costa Rica. Do you realize what your fans are experiencing?
The trip to Costa Rica is also our dream, which becomes a reality.
In South and Central America we are barely a second time and the experience so far has been great.
I've only been to Costa Rica once, on vacation. It's a beautiful country and I believe we'll be able to stay here for a few days.
So we are very happy to bring you our music.
I ask, because they literally love the group here, the fans are experiencing these days of preparation very intensely.
What do you say to your biggest fans?
Thank you for staying with us for so many years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica. Thank you for waiting so long and we're sorry that it took us so long.
Some people already talk about the concert as the biggest show of the year.
Does it put more pressure on you?
Some of the biggest shows we’ve performed in the last 21 years have been created over the course of a few weeks.
We have performed some great shows in Sao Paulo and we hope that this will get us into shape for a concert in Costa Rica.
We are really looking forward to this concert.
We love this country, we like to serve, we like the jungle. For both activities, Costa Rica is the best country in the world.
How did you get to know Costa Rica and its waves suitable for surfing?
We have a lot of surfer friends and I have a good friend who lives in Tamarindo. The waves here are incredible.
My friends go surfing in Costa Rica or Nicaragua or Mexico. These are the best places to surf. And so we learned about Costa Rica through people who love surfing.
If we look at your tour, you have prepared a huge show with many songs.
What did you plan for your presentation in Costa Rica?
Since we've never played here, we have no restrictions on what we can't do.
We will try to show the best show with a variety of songs. We will try to play a few songs from each album and present our fans with a good and diverse repertoire.
You will never repeat the repertoire.
- Why?
I think it’s partly because we have nine albums and we can play more than 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, so it’s hard to choose what songs we’re going to play every night.
When we have two or three songs in the repertoire that we haven’t played in a long time, we focus on them and we are also surprised because we will remember why we liked them so much and that we may have already forgotten about it.
So the show is more interesting for us, which is why I think it is more interesting for people too.
This tour celebrates 20 years of art.
When you look back, is it hard to believe everything you’ve done?
Yes, I'm sure you are.
First of all, I don't think any of us could have imagined that we'd be in one big rock band and that we'd be in it for more than 20 years.
We are aware of how much we have been given and we are impressed that we can continue to play together.
We love each other and we love making music.
We are lucky to be able to look at the places we have always longed for.
We couldn't have gotten better.
What did it mean to you that you were an important part of the creation of the grunge genre?
It has always been an honor for us to be part of this group, in which the greats themselves are represented.
People from Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains are our friends.
It’s surprising that when a movement arises from a group of friends, it doesn’t happen very often.
From time to time, a group is formed in the city, but it is much less common for five to ten groups to emerge from one city at a time.
We are proud of this and we are honored to be part of the Seattle group.
Sometimes we play with others.
Last year we were at the festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on tour. We are lucky that they are all our friends and we are honored that we can be part of this movement that originated in Seattle.
It is also very unusual for a group like yours to stay together and still have the same members after all these years.
Yes, the four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which in itself is a much longer time than the usual duration of the group.
I think that firstly, we are all lucky to be still in this world, and secondly, the fact that we are always interested in each other plays a role.
We are all close friends and thanks to this we have managed to open up musical paths that allow everyone enough freedom to experiment for themselves.
We trust each other, we value each other’s music, and I don’t think it could be any better.
Your relationship with the word fame has not been easy. However, thanks to your success you can do what you like.
How do you find balance?
As we grew up, it became increasingly easier to find balance.
We try not to drive too much on tour because it is very easy to fall into this trap of crowds and people who love our music.
When you realize that people came for music, you will remember that you have to respect the music and what you gave it. You must not be carried away by being famous, rock stars. None of us ever really cared about this.
What do you think of Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote great songs, and at the beginning it was something spectacular.
We’ve been together for three years and never released an album until after Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
It was very frustrating because it took so long. The most important thing is that we are still friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore) who started in the band with us today. When I listen to a song or look at the photos, I remember how happy Andy was.
She was an incredible person and we miss her so much.
The national band Las Robertas will be commissioned to start the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know their work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that that's why you chose them as the forerunners?
Yes, the production sent us videos with a few suggestions and we liked this group the most. Therefore, we are curious about what Las Robertas will offer live and they must be very entertaining.
Why do you always change the words Yellow Ledbetter live?
That's a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don't know.
He sings it and I think he adds the first thing he thinks.
Who is influencing you as a bass player?
Lots of people.
I'm the first to be attacked by Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C.J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could talk all night about the basics that I like.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep the grunge even though it is no longer in fashion?
I think we've always felt a little separated from the word grunge.
When it comes to grunge, I imagine bands I mentioned like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the others that were created at the same time. And if music like this is still valid today, it's something great, because it's music worth listening to and bands like Mudhoney are better than today.
In the beginning, your music was slightly gloomy in character and now it is more positive.
What is behind this change?
This is interesting because I feel like there are a few songs in the new album that are lighter to cut, but there are also songs like The End or Juste Breathe that are considered very gloomy, although they may sound positive.
For both of you, when Ed played them to me, I cried, and they're songs of deep darkness.
I think that when you grow up and have some trauma in your life, you lose someone from your family or a friend, these things start to affect your art and music, and these two songs represent that to me.
I also think you can be a happy person and still make dark music.
