Former President Alberto Fujimori was hospitalized in a public hospital on Tuesday, where he will be tested for muscle loss in his lower limbs, his attending physician said.
Fujimori, 72, who is serving a 25-year prison sentence for human rights violations committed by his government (1990-2000), suffers from several diseases, including tongue cancer, for which he has been operated on four times and is currently under the control of doctors.
Deputy Alejandro Aguinaga, who is his personal doctor, told Canal N television that Fujimori would undergo tests at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases in three days, where they should find out why he is in pain and why he is losing strength in the lower limbs.
Aguinaga said he believed Fujimori could be pardoned for humanitarian reasons, but the former president himself does not want pardon because he feels innocent.
He was operated on four times for tongue cancer, lost 18 kilograms and added other ailments such as severe erosive gastritis, cyst on the pancreas, kidney stones, high pressure and circulatory problems in the legs, the doctor said.
Fujimori has been serving his sentence since September 2007 at the National Directorate of Special Police Operations.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the deaths of 25 people killed by a murderous squadron of troops operating illegally in the early years of his government.
