Park or Mountain?
The architects met on the occasion of the proclamation, which brings with it more than a controversy about fees
The city’s 16-gate competition is once again opening a debate on the role of Collserola Park in Barcelona.
In the mid-1980s, at the time of the greatest flowering of the already extinct Corporaci<0xC3><0xB3>n Metropolitana de Barcelona (CMB), this self-government printed several pamphlets in support of the Collserola Park.
The flyer defined the mountain as a large park of the metropolitan Barcelona.
What’s more, it was supplemented by a numerical comparison with New York’s Central Park.
After the extinction of the CMB in 1987, the park returned to the minds of many as the upper limit of Barcelona. The Catalan metropolis is one of the few that is not oriented to the north - south axis, but up (mountain) - down (sea).
The qualification of Collserola as a natural park goes in this direction.
The reference was no longer Central Park, but Yellowstone with savages instead of the Yogi Bear.
That was the position until September, when the city hall announced a mega competition consisting of 16 competitions for the same number of entrance gates to Collserola.
The gate, of course, rather records the idea of the park.
Either this or someone is trying to put the gate on the field.
There is only one question: Collserola, a park or a mountain.
During the competition, both from a purely organizational point of view and based on reflection on the city, this question becomes the central theme of all Barcelona architects.
It’s already a topic as glaring as when two members of this old caste chosen to meet in an elevator shake hands.
And it was this act that sparked one of the rare coincidences between what the three Barcelona architects think and the prominent university professors.
Miguel Rold<0xC3><0xA1>n, Daniel Modol and Marta Bayona: the selection procedure is justified.
According to Rold<0xC3><0xA1>n, after the question of the Gulf side began, "it is necessary" to discuss the "mountain side" as well, so Ildefons Cerd's speech on green apples was not brought to an end.
"We have to start from the principle that the most extensive Barcelona park is the beach.
Among other things, its great availability.
Collserola is more complex," said the architect, for whom the name "gates to Collserola" bears "lexicological trap": we must not imagine them "as entrances to the park, but rather as the definition of zones where it is possible to act".
Modol, as well as Rold<0xC3><0xA1>n and Bayona with experience from the world of urbanism, classify the proposal as an "intellectual challenge" posing "some dangers".
The danger arising from the "uncertainty that the public space project presents today" after the experience of the 1980s, which had in the Forum area "its own swan singing".
The first concern is the very definition of the boundaries where it should be built.
“To define something is to take the next step,” that is, to move one step further.
"It is necessary to keep in mind the new urban and planning tools, because the current ones (with reference to the General Metropolitan Plan (PGM)) can cause a real disaster."
If we focus in more detail on the question, Modol believes that the Collserola valley slope can be "considered a park", but the Barcelona part is not, for purely topographical reasons.
Modol also recalled that there is already work done by the Patronat de Collserola, which "must not end up in the trash", although he welcomes the fact that the town hall offers his grammar to intervene in the project from "the first moment".
And moreover, he understands that the proximity of the mountain and the city is a kind of break that allows architects to get involved in the debate, but he "doubts" that it should be precisely this technical profile that will lead multidisciplinary teams ("it's all about skills", he adds) that need to be created: "Architects should only be tools."
Bayona suggests that the answer to the question that gave the title to this game is complex, because the global vision of Collserol is missing in the tender documents: "16 tenders were announced that dealt with all the axis of the mountain - the sea, but there is no longitudinal study that would address it as a field".
This means that at least he has applied to all 16 competitions.
Otherwise, the project of a single gate can affect the concept and definition of the architect of the neighboring gate.
According to him, the City Council should guarantee that the zone located directly above the Ronda de Dalt should provide for the entire length of the zone of equipment that would ensure a smooth transition between the city and the greenery.
