The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance has started research on the gene that causes obesity
The Institute of Health Insurance conducts research in order to discover the gene responsible for obesity in children and adolescents. The research is carried out with the support of experts from the IPN Institute
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it is conducting research to detect the gene causing obesity in children and adolescents. The research called "Genetics of Obesity in Children and Adolescents" will allow to obtain results related to overweight.
In a report by Miguel Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry at the National Health Center’s Specialized Hospital of the 21st Century, he explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been set up.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and from the Center for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
People can come to the IMSS sports centers in Valle de México, where they will be testing young people every 8 hours from 8:00 a.m. onwards.
He emphasized that the research began at the Cuauhtémoc Sports Center (Mexico State) and from October 8 this activity is also carried out at the Nezahualc<0xC3><0xB3>yolt Sports Center (East of Mexico State).
Once data from 500 to 600 children are obtained, the study will continue at the Independencia Sports Center (south of the Federal District) and finally at the Morelos Sports Center (north of the Federal Center).
He explained that the aim of this research is to determine the components and importance of genetics in terms of the development of obesity, and to trace risk factors on Mexican children and young people, thus preventing the development of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of International Diabetes Day, which is celebrated on 14 November, he recalled that the goal is to collect data from 3,000 children and young people between the ages of six and 14 years, with the consent and under the supervision of parents, for the application of specific questionnaires on nutrition.
The questionnaire will also ask about physical activity and family history of hereditary diseases in order to avoid risk factors that could cause diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He specified that every Saturday with all participants, anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure is measured, levels of glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin are determined and genes are examined (they try to identify genes that are involved in the formation).
Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez said the research reflects health care professionals' concern about the alarming increase in children's weight.
"Health surveys conducted between 1999 and 2006 showed that in just six years, only boys had a 77% increase in obesity and girls had a 47% increase in obesity, and there was also a dramatic increase in overweight," the IMSS expert said.
He said that one of the reasons for looking for indicators is the assumption that the population of the country differs from other populations by its genetic history.
He informed that the average Mexican has 65% Indian-American genetic equipment, 30% European and 5% African. This fact is reflected in the genes that are responsible for the development of diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity is commonly explained as the inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) and which is stored in the form of fats.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit of the participants is that they get an overall assessment of the condition of the children, which will determine whether they show any known overweight or obesity.
He said that even the presence of dark-colored wrinkles (acantosis) on the neck and forearm indicates the likelihood that the individual will suffer from metabolic problems and pre-diabetic conditions.
The information is so far confidential, doctors pass it on in writing to parents and explain to them all the measurements and lifestyle changes they need to make in order for their children to avoid the disease.
Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity, and other chronic diseases: a sedentary lifestyle signifying a lack of daily physical activity, day-to-day sitting in front of television, and the use of vehicles instead of walking for short distances.
Overweight also causes a large calorie intake, that is, a greater consumption of sweetened drinks, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins, and the genetic load that is the subject of this research.
Asphalt from UNAM will not be cleared
Rafael Herrera, a scientist from the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry, creates modified asphalts with polymers, thus creating a mixture with better functionality, regardless of climatic conditions and temperature
If the paving had been properly taken care of, it would not have been necessary to repair nearly 200,000 excavations after each rainy season in the Valle de México Metropolitan Area, said Rafael Herrera N<0xC3><0xA1>jera, a scientist from the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at UNAM, who added that from the construction and maintenance of the asphalt to the construction and maintenance of the asphalt.
In his lecture The Technological Cause of Excavations, which he delivered during the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory under his leadership is developing modified asphalts with polymers, thus creating a mixture having similar characteristics as asphalt, but at the same time a greater mechanical strength and durability.
Herrera N<0xC3><0xA1>jera believes that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places with an extremely warm climate, for example in some cities in the north of the country, thus improving functionality and reducing the formation of excavations.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a grouping of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with high molecular weight, called asphalts, and others with low molecular weight, called maltenes. Together they deliver a characteristic asphalt typical viscoelasticity.
The viscoelastic nature of asphalt lies in the fact that at high temperatures, around 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees it has a high viscosity and at 50 degrees it is almost in a solid state, while at low temperatures, asphalt tends to break, he added.
This means that the resistance of asphalt in the streets is not uniform, but changes during the day according to weather conditions and temperatures, the chemical engineering expert pointed out.
A scientist from the Faculty of Chemistry observed that most of the streets of Ciudad de México are covered with flexible tiles, consisting of six layers of materials, the last three of which are mixed with asphalt.
Among the topmost layers is an asphalt inlay, formed by small stones poured into the asphalt and then compressed.
He emphasized that every stone that forms the inlay is covered with asphalt.
When passing cars or when creating pressure, it is possible for the forces in the tiles to decompose well.
If it were a modified asphalt, they would decompose even better, the chemical engineer believes.
He added that on the asphalt inlay is placed the last layer called the shell, formed by a fine stone, that is, sand also poured into the asphalt.
Since this layer will come into contact with vehicle rims, it must have greater mechanical strength than the asphalt insert and must ensure friction of the roadway.
Since as part of the paving will be exposed to a large load, the jacket must be of sufficient thickness and attention must be paid to the material from which it is made.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature changes, are also a very important factor to keep in mind. In particular, water has a great impact on the functionality of the asphalt insert.
Once the ground is moist, the water spreads inwards and it is difficult to get out, it causes softening of all layers of the tile and thus the formation of debris.
He explained that during the formation of the excavations, the film of the mantle is first damaged and then the asphalt insert is damaged. However, the damage does not occur at one moment, but it is a gradual process that should stop at the first marks with appropriate maintenance programs.
As a member of the National System of Scientists, he also explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor in the formation of excavations, and therefore the thickness of each individual layer of tile must correspond to the load of vehicles and must be ensured that this load does not exceed the load.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that in terms of asphalt, we still have a lot of work to do and research is at the beginning. It is worth mentioning, for example, asphalt emulsions, which are already available on the market in other countries and make it easy to repair effluents without having to use high temperatures.
