Nord Stream, the new port of entry of Russian gas to Europe
The Nord Stream long-distance gas pipeline connecting Eastern Europe directly to Russia and running along the bottom of the Baltic Sea began to operate.
They have to supply gas equivalent to 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event properly.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, attended the inauguration of Nord Stream, a new pipeline that connects Russia and Germany under the sea.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte turned the control valve of the Russian gas inlet to the Western European network together.
This new gas pipeline will begin flowing 27.5 billion additional cubic meters of Russian gas into Western Europe each year through the first 1,224 km long pipeline connecting the St. Petersburg region with the Mecklenburg-Vorpommern state.
The second pipeline, to be completed at the end of 2012, will provide a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, which is equivalent to the total French consumption.
And it is already recalled the possibility of building the third pipeline on the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge building has the character of victory.
Poland and the Baltic states protested strongly against the project.
In fact, Nord Stream will make it possible to deliver gas directly to Germany without being led around the country by any third country (Poland or Ukraine).
At the same time, the two countries are losing some power: the ability to pressure Russia with threats to close its access to Western European markets is becoming more difficult for them.
Warsaw expressed this most strongly when it did not hesitate to compare Nord Stream to the "new German-Soviet pact", with reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin during the occupation of Poland in 1939.
This means that it is a politically sensitive issue.
Western Europe, with its support for this Russian project, has gained greater confidence in its purchases.
But it is at the cost of weakening Europe’s energy, as the project has created rifts between Europeans from the east and the west.
Just five years ago, Russia was able to enforce its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the wealthy, gas-intensive Western countries, whose deposits are nearing their end.
"This pipeline is part of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that organically connects us," Fillon said at the opening ceremony, demonstrating at what point large gas contracts are both political and economic.
All of this explains the broad smiles of Gazprom’s leaders present in large numbers in Lubmin, a gas supply site.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also an important technical act.
The underwater pipe is made of steel with a concrete shell to protect it from the anchors of naval vessels.
It lies at the bottom of the sea at an average depth of 200 m.
During its construction, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to World War II.
“For security reasons, almost a hundred of them had to be removed or destroyed,” said Jens Müller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
Measures to protect fauna and flora had to be increased as well.
The pipe itself is a long metal hose weighing as much as 242 Eiffel Towers, which in its entire length is not interrupted by valves or maintenance stations.
One control platform was supposed to be built near Sweden, but the project manager rejected it when the Swedes were only unwilling to see the Russian state-owned company permanently settle off their coast.
“In the event of a failure, we will stop the gas flow in less than 1 minute,” explains Jens Müller.
In case of leakage, the gas contained in the gas pipeline leaks into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the builder, because the welds were designed to create a leak once every 100,000 years.
The state of the gas pipeline is controlled from the outside by an underwater robot pulled by a ship, while the inside of the gas pipeline is controlled by a device that circulates inside.
This cigar-shaped device with a diameter of 1 meter is inserted into the inside of the pipe and is pressed with gas.
In the target after three full days of travel at a speed of 3 m/s, it will provide accurate information about possible deformations of metal parts.
The long-distance gas pipeline was designed to operate for fifty years without requiring the slightest repair.
The circulation of the gas is simply ensured by pressure.
The value of this pressure is 200 bar at the start and 100 bar at the finish.
Five companies joined forces to implement this project.
Gazprom, which holds a 51% stake, remains in the lead.
It was joined by German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as Dutch company Gasunie and French group GDF Suez (9% each).
The five companies created a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the pipeline.
The company is headquartered in the city of Zug in Switzerland, where taxation is extremely advantageous.
Gazprom subsequently leased the company all its gas transportation capacity for five years under a contract that could be renewed.
“Gazprom will benefit from the total capacity, whatever the amount of gas actually transported,” says Jens Müller.
The financing of the construction of the gas pipeline was provided by 30% shareholders and by 70% bank loans.
The total cost of work is expected to reach <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.4 billion for both pipelines.
For the GDF Suez Group, the investment costs amounted to 240 million euros.
But minority shareholders are confident that their costs will be reimbursed, as only Gazprom takes the risk.
The pipeline exits from the Baltic Sea in Lubmin on the sandy coast with pine forests.
The valves of 4.5 meters high form the outlet gate of the gas.
The sensors measure the pressure, temperature and other characteristics of the incoming gas before it is transported to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal receives one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and 6 million in 2012.
